abstract: The candidates said Attorney General William Barr’s summary of Robert Mueller’s investigation was inadequate.
snippet: The candidates said Attorney General William Barr’s summary of Robert Mueller’s investigation was inadequate.
lead_paragraph: Many Democratic presidential candidates on Sunday called for the release of the special counsel’s entire report and said they were dissatisfied with relying on Attorney General William P. Barr’s four-page summary of the two-year investigation.

abstract: On the surface, the annual Aipac conference looks relatively unchanged. But recent actions by President Trump and rising criticism of Israel on the left are taking a toll.
snippet: On the surface, the annual Aipac conference looks relatively unchanged. But recent actions by President Trump and rising criticism of Israel on the left are taking a toll.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — More than 18,000 activists will converge in Washington on Sunday for the annual conference of the American Israel Public Affairs Committee, as Democrats wrestle with the left’s rising criticism of Israel and as President Trump seeks to divide his political rivals while bolstering Israel’s embattled leader.

abstract: Unlike Obamacare, emerging plans would sweep away the private health insurance system. What would that mean for the companies’ workers, the stock market and the cost of care?
snippet: Unlike Obamacare, emerging plans would sweep away the private health insurance system. What would that mean for the companies’ workers, the stock market and the cost of care?
lead_paragraph: At the heart of the “Medicare for all” proposals championed by Senator Bernie Sanders and many Democrats is a revolutionary idea: Abolish private health insurance.

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From the Mueller report to the Democratic primary, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: Democratic candidates sought to use the report to build up their email lists of potential supporters who can be targeted with future fund-raising solicitations.
snippet: Democratic candidates sought to use the report to build up their email lists of potential supporters who can be targeted with future fund-raising solicitations.
lead_paragraph: CHARLESTON, S.C. — Democratic presidential candidates wasted no time Friday evening demanding the immediate public release of the long-awaited report from Robert S. Mueller III, with several saying that Americans deserved to know any findings about President Trump, Russia and the 2016 election in order to form judgments about Mr. Trump and the 2020 race.

abstract: Where is the Republican — or Democrat — willing to break with the base?
snippet: Where is the Republican — or Democrat — willing to break with the base?
lead_paragraph: In 1992, recording artist Lisa Williamson, better known as Sister Souljah, opined, “If black people kill black people every day, why not have a week and kill white people?” She also said, “If there are any good white people, I haven’t met them.”

abstract: The attorney general, William P. Barr, will determine how much of the special counsel’s Russia report will be shared with Congress or the public.
snippet: The attorney general, William P. Barr, will determine how much of the special counsel’s Russia report will be shared with Congress or the public.
lead_paragraph: Mr. Mueller did not suggest additional charges as part of his investigation, when he delivered his findings to Mr. Barr on Friday. This caps the special counsel’s charges at 199, filed against 34 people and three companies.
